                                  "favorite_count": 28,
                                  "favorited": false,
                                  "full_text": "to predict the future you have to build a model that corresponds to features of reality and play it forward faster than time advances in reality so you can make the prediction before the event occurs. \n\nmodel fidelity depends on scale and choosing the right abstractions, as the",
                                  "id_str": "2055287318899003901",
                                  "is_quote_status": false,
                                  "lang": "en",
                                  "quote_count": 0,
                                  "reply_count": 7,
                                  "retweet_count": 2,
                                  "retweeted": false,
                                  "user_id_str": "1378862677871751174"
                                },
                                "note_tweet": {
                                  "is_expandable": true,
                                  "note_tweet_results": {
                                    "result": {
                                      "entity_set": {
                                        "hashtags": [],
                                        "smarttags": [],
                                        "symbols": [],
                                        "urls": [],
                                        "user_mentions": []
                                      },
                                      "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNTUyODczMTg3ODU3ODU4NTc=",
                                      "text": "to predict the future you have to build a model that corresponds to features of reality and play it forward faster than time advances in reality so you can make the prediction before the event occurs. \n\nmodel fidelity depends on scale and choosing the right abstractions, as the model scales at some point it becomes more of a simulation.  but if it fits within the system being modeled and runs fast enough to make useful predictions it has to be way smaller than reality. \n\nplanning is prediction with branching between alternate actions an agent might take. we all plan all the time- worrying, daydreaming, rehearsing our future behavior. i expect all intelligent agents would. \n\nsometimes i wonder if our whole reality is a simulation running inside the mind of a superintelligence"
                                    }
                                  }
                                },
                                "rest_id": "2055287318899003901",
